SIMPLE: excitement
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Excitement
<hw>Ex*cite"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OF.
<ets>excitement</ets>, <ets>escitement</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of exciting, or the state of being roused into action, or
of having increased action; impulsion; agitation; <as>as, an
<ex>excitement</ex> of the people</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which excites or rouses; that which moves,
stirs, or induces action; a motive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cares and <qex>excitements</qex> of a season of transition and
struggle.</q> <rj><qau>Talfowrd.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A state of aroused or
increased vital activity in an organism, or any of its organs or
tissues.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exciter</ent>⟦br⟧
